","Accessory","Hypoglossal"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eglossopharyngeal nerve\u003C/strong\u003E (CN IX) provides sensory innervation to the posterior third of the tongue and motor innervation to the stylopharyngeus muscle. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eaccessory nerve\u003C/strong\u003E (CN XI) innervates the sternocleidomastoid and trapezius muscles. The \u003Cstrong\u003Ehypoglossal nerve\u003C/strong\u003E (CN XII) provides motor innervation to all intrinsic and extrinsic muscles of the tongue except palatoglossus.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EWhen there is unilateral hypoglossal nerve damage, the tongue deviates toward the side of the lesion due to unopposed contraction of the contralateral genioglossus muscle. The \u003Cstrong\u003Evagus nerve\u003C/strong\u003E (CN X) innervates the muscles of the soft palate, pharynx, and larynx. The \u003Cstrong\u003Efacial nerve\u003C/strong\u003E (CN VII) provides motor innervation to the muscles of facial expression and carries taste fibres from the anterior two-thirds of the tongue.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The hypoglossal nerve (cranial nerve XII) innervates all intrinsic and extrinsic muscles of the tongue except palatoglossus","Unilateral hypoglossal nerve damage causes ipsilateral tongue deviation due to unopposed contraction of the contralateral genioglossus muscle"],"references":["Reese V, Das JM, Al Khalili Y. Cranial Nerve Testing. [Updated 2023 May 6]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK585066/","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevisi